# GoDaddy vs AWS — Simple Explanation

GoDaddy and AWS serve different roles in a web platform. They work together but are not the same.

## GoDaddy

GoDaddy is primarily a **Domain Registrar and DNS provider**.

Its main responsibility is managing internet domain names.

Example:
olivine.co.in

What GoDaddy typically handles:

• Domain registration (ownership of the domain name)
• DNS records (A, CNAME, MX, TXT etc.)
• Email hosting (like [viji@olivine.co.in](mailto:viji@olivine.co.in))
• Basic website hosting services

In the Olivine setup, GoDaddy currently manages:

• Domain ownership → olivine.co.in
• DNS routing → subdomains pointing to AWS
• Email → [viji@olivine.co.in](mailto:viji@olivine.co.in)

You can think of GoDaddy as **the address manager of your website**.

---

## AWS (Amazon Web Services)

AWS is a **cloud infrastructure platform** that runs applications and servers.

It provides computing infrastructure for building and running software.

Common AWS services include:

• Elastic Beanstalk → application hosting
• EC2 → virtual servers
• S3 → storage
• RDS → databases
• CloudFront → content delivery network

In the Olivine setup, AWS runs:

• The Django application
• Gunicorn server
• Elastic Beanstalk deployment environment
• S3 backup storage

AWS is essentially **the data center where your software runs**.

---

## How They Work Together

User opens a browser and enters:

olivine.co.in

Flow:

User Browser
→ GoDaddy DNS resolves the domain
→ Subdomain routes to AWS Elastic Beanstalk
→ Elastic Beanstalk runs Gunicorn
→ Gunicorn runs the Django application

So the responsibilities are:

GoDaddy → Domain and DNS management
AWS → Application hosting and infrastructure

---

## Simple Summary

GoDaddy = Internet Address (Domain & DNS)
AWS = Cloud Servers (Application & Infrastructure)


What the Records Mean

The entries like:

crm   → CNAME → vijim-ai-prod.eba-smvi2mvs.us-east-1.elasticbeanstalk.com
erp   → CNAME → vijim-ai-prod.eba-smvi2mvs.us-east-1.elasticbeanstalk.com
fms   → CNAME → vijim-ai-prod.eba-smvi2mvs.us-east-1.elasticbeanstalk.com
hrm   → CNAME → vijim-ai-prod.eba-smvi2mvs.us-east-1.elasticbeanstalk.com
meet  → CNAME → vijim-ai-prod.eba-smvi2mvs.us-east-1.elasticbeanstalk.com

mean that the following URLs will all point to the same AWS Elastic Beanstalk environment:

crm.olivine.co.in
erp.olivine.co.in
fms.olivine.co.in
hrm.olivine.co.in
meet.olivine.co.in

So when a user visits any of these, the request goes:

Browser
   ↓
GoDaddy DNS
   ↓
Elastic Beanstalk hostname
   ↓
Your Django application
The email Record
email → CNAME → email.secureserver.net

This is for GoDaddy webmail access, not your application.

Example:

email.olivine.co.in

opens GoDaddy email login.

Your mailbox:

viji@olivine.co.in

remains unaffected.

What This Confirms

Your DNS layer is now correctly wired:

✔ Subdomains → Elastic Beanstalk
✔ Email → GoDaddy mail server
✔ TTL → 1 hour (normal)

The Only Remaining Issue

Your deployment problem is not DNS anymore.

It is this:

Gunicorn cannot find module: vijim_ai

That means the problem is inside AWS Elastic Beanstalk, not GoDaddy.

Most likely one of these:

Procfile path
WSGI path
Project folder structure
PYTHONPATH
Quick Test You Can Do Now

Try opening these in your browser:

erp.olivine.co.in
crm.olivine.co.in
app.olivine.co.in

You will likely see one of these:

• EB default page
• 502 Bad Gateway
• Application error

All of these confirm DNS works but Django hasn’t started.

